cess2star  aThis electronic version has been made available under a Creative Commons (BY-NC-ND) open access license. Never before have the scope and limits of scientific freedom been more important or more under attack. New science, from artificial intelligence to gene editing, creates unique opportunities for making the world a better place. It also presents unprecedented dangers. This book is about the opportunities and challenges - moral, regulatory and existential - that face both science and society. How are scientific developments impacting on human life and on the structure of societies? How is science regulated and how should it be regulated? Are there ethical boundaries to scientific developments in sensitive areas? Such are the questions that the book seeks to answer. Both the survival of humankind and the continued existence of our planet are at stake.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aSocial sciences. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Research.2bisacsh  aRegulation of science.  aScience and society.  aScientific freedom.1 aAas, Sean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaldoli, Roberto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBallabeni, Andrea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoggio, Andrea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrassington, Iain, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCappato, Marco, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCorbellini, Gilberto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCutas, Daniela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/